anings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Pérez</b> (see   Perez  ).","Czech (<b>Pařez</b>): nickname from <i>pařez</i> ‘(tree) stump’.","In some cases possibly also French (Nord), Walloon, and Flemish: variant of <b>Paré</b> (see   Pare  ) or   Paret  ."]},{"name":"Peter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Ernst, Fritz, Heinz, Helmut, Horst, Kaspar, Klaus, Siegfried, Wolfgang.","English, Scottish, German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), Czech (Moravian), Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian; Hungarian (<b>Péter</b>): from the personal name <i>Peter</i> (Greek <i>Petros</i>, from <i>petra</i> ‘rock’). The personal name was popular throughout Christian Europe in the Middle Ages, having been bestowed by Christ as a byname on the apostle Simon bar Jonah, the brother of Andrew. The name was chosen by Christ for its symbolic significance (John 1:42, Matt. 16:18); Saint Peter is regarded as the founding head of the Christian Church in view of Christ's saying, ‘Thou art Peter and upon this rock I will build my Church’. In Christian Germany in the early Middle Ages this was the most frequent personal name of non-ancient Germanic origin until the 14th century. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Czech   Petr  , Polish <b>Piotr</b> and <b>Pietr</b>, Albanian <b>Pjetri</b> (from the personal name <i>Pjetër</i>, definite form <i>Pjetri</i>), and also their derivatives (see examples at   Peterson  ). It has also been adopted as a surname by Ashkenazic Jews."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which was originally a nickname from an English dialect word meaning ‘fox’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354684,"age":97,"year":"1200","julianDay":2159351,"description":"The Christian territory controlled the Kingdoms of Aragon, Navarre, and Castile.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Toda Pérez de Arazuri was born in Arazuri, Oltza Zendea, Nafarroa, Spain as the daughter of Pedro de Arazuri Señor de Artajona, Tudela y Daroca and Mrs Pedro De Arazuri. She married Pedro Ruíz de Azagra, I Señor de Albarracín y II Señoror de Estella about 1122, in Spain. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 4 daughters."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–1186":"–1186","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1129–Female":"1129–Surnud","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1085–1183":"1085–1183","aproximadamente 1122":"umbes 1122","about 1160":"umbes 1160","about1148":"umbes 1100","1186":"1186","1152":"1152","1085":"1085","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1129":"1129","1216":"1216","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","about 1152":"umbes 1152","Arazuri, Nafarroa, Hispania":"Arazuri, Oltza Zendea, Nafarroa, Hispaania","España":"Hispaania","Azagra, Nafarroa, Spain":"Azagra, Nafarroa, Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–1186":"–1186","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1129–Female":"1129–Kuollut","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1085–1183":"1085–1183","aproximadamente 1122":"noin 1122","about 1160":"noin 1160","about1148":"noin 1100","1186"